                <head>269. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On November 25, President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> sent
                    a message to Guinean President <persName corresp="#p_TAS1">Sékou
                        Touré</persName> replying to a November 20 cable from <persName
                        corresp="#p_TAS1">Touré</persName>. In that message, <persName
                        corresp="#p_TAS1">Touré</persName> charged that the United States had taken
                    a “partisan position” and was supporting “the enemies of African emancipation”
                    in the Congo and threatened that if the United Stated maintained its position,
                    Guinea would refuse to take part in the Conciliation Commission and would take
                    “any position in African affairs consistent with Congolese interests.” President
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>’s reply declared that the
                    United States had “been in the forefront of those nations who have favored
                    emancipation of all peoples” and urged Guinean support to the U.N. effort in the
                    Congo. For texts of both messages, see <hi rend="italic">American Foreign
                        Policy: Current Documents, 1960,</hi> pages 601–602.</p>
            </div>
